ngland":"Dorchester, Dorset, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1525–7 Jun 1607":"1525–7. juni 1607","1525–1587":"1525–1587","1548–1618":"1548–1618","1525–1607":"1525–1607","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","7 Jun 1607":"7. juni 1607","6 June 1587":"6. juni 1587","1571":"1571","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","St. George, Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1525–7 Jun 1607":"1525–7 juni 1607","1525–1587":"1525–1587","1548–1618":"1548–1618","1525–1607":"1525–1607","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","7 Jun 1607":"7 juni 1607","6 June 1587":"6 juni 1587","1571":"1571","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","St. George, Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1525–7 Jun 1607":"1525–7 June 1607","1525–1587":"1525–1587","1548–1618":"1548–1618","1525–1607":"1525–1607","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","7 Jun 1607":"7 June 1607","6 June 1587":"6 June 1587","1571":"1571","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","St. George, Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ainge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: shortened form of <b>Ainger</b>, itself a variant of   Angier  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Angier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre.","French and English (of Norman and French Huguenot origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Angier</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>ans</i> ‘god’ + <i>ger</i> ‘spear’ (Old Norse <i>geirr</i>)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Eames","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":24,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":33,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":44,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":46,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":75,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Thomas Eames Ainge was born in 1525, in Fordington, Dorset, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Joan Fiske. He died on 7 June 1607, in Dorchester, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 82, and was buried in Fordington, Dorset, England."},"et":{"1525–7 Jun 1607":"1525–7. juuni 1607","1525–1587":"1525–1587","1548–1618":"1548–1618","1525–1607":"1525–1607","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","7 Jun 1607":"7. juuni 1607","6 June 1587":"6. juuni 1587","1571":"1571","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","St. George, Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1525–7 Jun 1607":"1525–7. kesäkuuta 1607","1525–1587":"1525–1587","1548–1618":"1548–1618","1525–1607":"1525–1607","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1587":"1587","7 Jun 1607":"7. kesäkuuta 1607","6 June 1587":"6. kesäkuuta 1587","1571":"1571","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","St. George, Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Fordington, Dorset, England":"Fordington, Dorset, England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt 